\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Per-chromosome HCCP coverage on chrom-LOO ($\alpha = 0.10$, $K = 5$, target $= 0.90$). \textbf  {(a, b) Forest plots} (sorted ascending by HCCP coverage). Filled circles: HCCP point estimate; horizontal bars: 95\% within-chrom bootstrap CI ($B = 1000$); open squares: split-CP coverage on the same chromosome (overlaid for context, both methods are marginal-cov calibrated). Light shading: $\pm 0.03$ band around target; dashed line: $1{-}\alpha = 0.90$. On Mendelian, the worst chromosome chr6 ($\mathrm  {cov} = 0.80$, $n = 30$) has a 95\% CI $[0.63, 0.93]$ that \emph  {crosses} the target, so its under-coverage is not statistically distinguishable from binomial noise; all other Mendelian chromosomes' CIs intersect or fall within the $\pm 0.03$ band. Complex is tight: all 22 chromosomes' CIs lie within $\pm 0.04$ of target. \textbf  {(c, d) Coverage vs.\ $n_c$} (per-chromosome variant count, log-scaled). Dotted band: $\pm 1.96 \sqrt  {p(1-p)/n_c}$ binomial finite-sample envelope at $p = 0.90$. Every chromosome on both datasets sits inside the envelope, including the Mendelian outliers (top 3 by $|\mathrm  {gap}|$ labeled). The cross-chromosome variability is therefore a sample-size effect rather than a method failure; this is exactly the regime in which T3$'$'s robust certificate (Thm.\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {thm:t3prime_main}) supplies a uniform finite-sample lower bound, while T3's exact bin-conditional bound widens by $1/(n_{\qopname  \relax m{min}}+1)$ on the smallest cells.}}{28}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:per_chrom}{{2}{28}{Per-chromosome HCCP coverage on chrom-LOO ($\alpha = 0.10$, $K = 5$, target $= 0.90$). \textbf {(a, b) Forest plots} (sorted ascending by HCCP coverage). Filled circles: HCCP point estimate; horizontal bars: 95\% within-chrom bootstrap CI ($B = 1000$); open squares: split-CP coverage on the same chromosome (overlaid for context, both methods are marginal-cov calibrated). Light shading: $\pm 0.03$ band around target; dashed line: $1{-}\alpha = 0.90$. On Mendelian, the worst chromosome chr6 ($\mathrm {cov} = 0.80$, $n = 30$) has a 95\% CI $[0.63, 0.93]$ that \emph {crosses} the target, so its under-coverage is not statistically distinguishable from binomial noise; all other Mendelian chromosomes' CIs intersect or fall within the $\pm 0.03$ band. Complex is tight: all 22 chromosomes' CIs lie within $\pm 0.04$ of target. \textbf {(c, d) Coverage vs.\ $n_c$} (per-chromosome variant count, log-scaled). Dotted band: $\pm 1.96 \sqrt {p(1-p)/n_c}$ binomial finite-sample envelope at $p = 0.90$. Every chromosome on both datasets sits inside the envelope, including the Mendelian outliers (top 3 by $|\mathrm {gap}|$ labeled). The cross-chromosome variability is therefore a sample-size effect rather than a method failure; this is exactly the regime in which T3$'$'s robust certificate (Thm.~\ref {thm:t3prime_main}) supplies a uniform finite-sample lower bound, while T3's exact bin-conditional bound widens by $1/(n_{\min }+1)$ on the smallest cells}{figure.2}{}}
