\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces HCCP vs DEGU-lite on the (efficiency, $\hat  {\sigma }$-bin coverage gap) Pareto plane. X-axis: singleton fraction (variants receiving a confident $\{0\}$ or $\{1\}$ set rather than the abstention $\{0,1\}$); higher is more efficient. Y-axis: worst $\hat  {\sigma }$-bin coverage gap (lower is better). The shaded \emph  {ideal zone} marks the bottom-right corner (high efficiency $+$ low gap). \textbf  {Iso-cost diagonals} $L = \mathrm  {gap} + 0.05\,(1-\mathrm  {eff})$ convert the plane to a topographic view: points on the same dashed line have equal operational cost; points below a line dominate it. The slope $\lambda = 0.05$ is set by the headline operating point ($\mathrm  {gap}_{\qopname  \relax m{max}} = 0.04$ at singleton$\,= 0.80$), so a 1-pp efficiency change is cost-equal to a $0.0005$ gap change. Per-point $L$ annotations rank the four cells: \textbf  {HCCP-Complex} $L = 0.052$ (in ideal zone); \textbf  {HCCP-Mendelian} / \textbf  {DEGU-Mendelian} $L = 0.051 / 0.044$ (near-tie); \textbf  {DEGU-Complex} $L = 0.090$ (dominated). On \textbf  {Complex}, HCCP is $\sim 4\times $ smaller gap than DEGU-lite at matched efficiency, confirming the aleatoric-dominated regime favours supervised $\hat  {\sigma }$; on \textbf  {Mendelian}, DEGU is marginally below HCCP (0.033 vs.\ 0.041) since monogenic signal makes ensemble disagreement a near-equivalent proxy. Both methods avoid the high-gap, low-efficiency corner that homoscedastic split-CP and class-Mondrian baselines occupy in Tab.\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:h2h} and Tab.\nobreakspace  {}\ref  {tab:cp_baselines}.}}{33}{figure.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:pareto_degu}{{5}{33}{HCCP vs DEGU-lite on the (efficiency, $\shat $-bin coverage gap) Pareto plane. X-axis: singleton fraction (variants receiving a confident $\{0\}$ or $\{1\}$ set rather than the abstention $\{0,1\}$); higher is more efficient. Y-axis: worst $\shat $-bin coverage gap (lower is better). The shaded \emph {ideal zone} marks the bottom-right corner (high efficiency $+$ low gap). \textbf {Iso-cost diagonals} $L = \mathrm {gap} + 0.05\,(1-\mathrm {eff})$ convert the plane to a topographic view: points on the same dashed line have equal operational cost; points below a line dominate it. The slope $\lambda = 0.05$ is set by the headline operating point ($\mathrm {gap}_{\max } = 0.04$ at singleton$\,= 0.80$), so a 1-pp efficiency change is cost-equal to a $0.0005$ gap change. Per-point $L$ annotations rank the four cells: \textbf {HCCP-Complex} $L = 0.052$ (in ideal zone); \textbf {HCCP-Mendelian} / \textbf {DEGU-Mendelian} $L = 0.051 / 0.044$ (near-tie); \textbf {DEGU-Complex} $L = 0.090$ (dominated). On \textbf {Complex}, HCCP is $\sim 4\times $ smaller gap than DEGU-lite at matched efficiency, confirming the aleatoric-dominated regime favours supervised $\shat $; on \textbf {Mendelian}, DEGU is marginally below HCCP (0.033 vs.\ 0.041) since monogenic signal makes ensemble disagreement a near-equivalent proxy. Both methods avoid the high-gap, low-efficiency corner that homoscedastic split-CP and class-Mondrian baselines occupy in Tab.~\ref {tab:h2h} and Tab.~\ref {tab:cp_baselines}}{figure.5}{}}
